Where do I even start. These are the perfect subs. I catch myself in a daydream over the egg salad. The roast beef a rarity. The tuna salad top notch. You’ve never had a properly stacked hoagie until you’ve had The Teamster. The Compliments Only crew are mavens of their trade. Best subs in town.

Better than most, worse than some.  The sandwiches were well constructed with quality ingredients, but definitely miss a crave-able factor. If you’re in the neighborhood, it’s worth stopping by for a bite or some takeaway.

A beloved hidden gem in Washington, D.C. is a small market in Eckington called Yang Market. Inside is a surprisingly good deli. The man behind its top-rated sandwiches now has his own shop on 14th Street in Logan Circle- Compliments Only. It's so small that it's easy to miss, but don't. Right before you hit R Street NW there's a brightly painted enclave with a gym and Compliments Only.  Once inside, you'll see a tiny space with a counter, kitchen space and a refrigerator with sodas and other drinks. Staff are masked and gloved and the menu is on the counter in plain view by the register.  The menu includes seven sandwiches with names like "The Teamster" (their version of an Italian hoagie) and "Nancy Pelosi Eats Free." Sandwiches range between $11.50 and $14. Chips are an additional $3.25 and drinks are between $1.50-$3.  I ordered the "Nancy Pelosi Eats Free" and a soda. The sub was well-balanced and the honey chili aioli gave it flavor and a slight kick. It's not the biggest sandwich you'll order in the city, but I didn't leave hungry. They stamp a compliment on the outside of each sub, which I needed after the terrorism that happened at the U.S. Capitol this past week.  There are tables and chairs outside if you want to stay and eat.

Really pricey subs but the ingredients seemed high quality. I wasn’t thrilled with the amount of oil/vinegar they put on my sub, it was drenched in oil and they don’t provide any napkins for takeout orders so it was super messy.

Grabbed a couple subs to go after reading the Eater DC article and Compliments Only didn’t disappoint.  We got the Marissa Tomei Eats Free and The Teamster, both were packed with well balanced high quality toppings that traveled really well. Give them a try next time your sandwich craving hits.
